          "label": "<p>In a transverse section of the lower pons, which fibre bundle connects the abduc</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In a transverse section of the lower pons, which fibre bundle connects the abducens nucleus to the contralateral oculomotor nucleus for coordinated horizontal gaze?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Medial lemniscus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The medial lemniscus carries fine touch and proprioception from the body. It runs as a horizontal strip in the dorsal tegmentum but plays no role in gaze coordination.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Transverse pontine fibres</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Transverse pontine fibres carry cortical relay signals from the pontine nuclei to the contralateral cerebellar hemisphere via the middle cerebellar peduncle — they are part of the corticopontocerebellar pathway.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Medial longitudinal fasciculus</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! The MLF links the abducens nucleus (CN VI) in the pons to the contralateral oculomotor nucleus (CN III) in the midbrain. This connection ensures that when one eye abducts, the other simultaneously adducts for conjugate horizontal gaze.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Trapezoid body</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The trapezoid body carries auditory fibres crossing the midline from the cochlear nuclei. It is part of the ascending auditory pathway, not the oculomotor system.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The correct answer is the medial longitudinal fasciculus (MLF). It connects the abducens nucleus to the contralateral oculomotor nucleus, enabling coordinated horizontal eye movements."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done! The MLF is the backbone of conjugate horizontal gaze, linking CN VI to the contralateral CN III."
                }
              ],
              "behaviour": {
