          "label": "<p>Which clinical feature distinguishes Millard-Gubler syndrome from Raymond syndro</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which clinical feature distinguishes Millard-Gubler syndrome from Raymond syndrome?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Contralateral hemiplegia</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Contralateral hemiplegia from corticospinal tract damage is present in both syndromes and therefore cannot distinguish between them.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Ipsilateral lower motor neuron facial palsy</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! Millard-Gubler syndrome involves damage to the seventh nerve fascicles, producing ipsilateral LMN facial palsy. Raymond syndrome spares CN VII entirely — this single difference is the key distinguishing feature.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Ipsilateral lateral rectus palsy</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Ipsilateral lateral rectus palsy from CN VI damage is common to both Raymond and Millard-Gubler syndromes. It does not help differentiate them.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Contralateral loss of fine touch and proprioception</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Contralateral sensory loss from medial lemniscus involvement is a feature of Foville syndrome, which is a more extensive lesion than either Raymond or Millard-Gubler.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The answer is ipsilateral lower motor neuron facial palsy. Both syndromes share lateral rectus palsy and contralateral hemiplegia; Millard-Gubler adds CN VII fascicle damage causing facial palsy, while Raymond does not."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly right. The presence of ipsilateral LMN facial palsy is what separates Millard-Gubler from the simpler Raymond syndrome."
                }
              ],
