          "label": "<p>What makes the mesencephalic nucleus of the trigeminal nerve unique among all cr</p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>What makes the mesencephalic nucleus of the trigeminal nerve unique among all cranial nerve nuclei?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>It carries taste sensation from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Taste from the anterior two-thirds of the tongue is carried by the chorda tympani branch of CN VII and relayed to the nucleus tractus solitarius, not the mesencephalic nucleus.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It is the only cranial nerve nucleus found exclusively in the medulla</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The mesencephalic nucleus is located in the midbrain and upper pons, not the medulla. Several nuclei exist in the medulla (e.g., hypoglossal, dorsal vagal), but location alone is not what makes this nucleus unique.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>It contains parasympathetic preganglionic neurons</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Parasympathetic preganglionic neurons are found in the Edinger-Westphal nucleus (CN III), superior salivatory nucleus (CN VII), and inferior salivatory nucleus (CN IX) — not the mesencephalic nucleus.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Its first-order sensory neurons are located within the central nervous system</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! In every other sensory pathway, first-order neuron cell bodies reside in peripheral ganglia (e.g., dorsal root ganglia, trigeminal ganglion). The mesencephalic nucleus is the sole exception — its primary neurons carrying jaw proprioception sit within the brainstem itself.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The answer is that its first-order sensory neurons are located within the CNS. All other sensory nerves have their primary neuron cell bodies in peripheral ganglia — the mesencephalic nucleus is the sole exception, housing proprioceptive neurons for the jaw muscles."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Well done! The mesencephalic nucleus is the only place in the CNS where primary sensory neuron cell bodies reside, carrying proprioception from the muscles of mastication."
                }
              ],
